{"key":"post-9884864","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9884864</id>\n<content>You can use a salamander type construction heater to heat up a whole storage shed.&amp;nbsp; You could put your manure substrates in trays on shelves, and then heat the entire building up to about 190F and leave it there for 12 to 24 hours.&amp;nbsp; You can pasteurize a few thousand pounds that way.&amp;nbsp; Those heaters run on propane or kerosene and cost about $300.&amp;nbsp; This is how many small commercial mushroom farms do it.&amp;nbsp; You cut a round hole in the side of the storage shed for the output end of the salamander to poke through, while the main part of the unit remains outside.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9884886</next>\n<prev>9884794</prev>\n<first>9884298</first>\n<last>9919643</last>\n<when>1235856991</when>\n<utime>02/28/09 11:36 PM</utime>\n</post>"}